90th, 95th, 99th percentile (very important in interviews) yes

In Apache JMeter performance reports, 90th, 95th, and 99th percentiles are extremely important metrics. Many companies (especially for APIs, banking apps, and large websites) rely on percentiles instead of averages because averages can hide slow responses.

Let’s break it down clearly.

1. What is Percentile in Performance Testing

A percentile tells you how many requests completed within a certain response time.

Example idea:

If 95th percentile = 2 seconds

➡ 95% of requests finished in ≤ 2 seconds
➡ 5% of requests took longer than 2 seconds

This helps detect slow outliers.

2. Simple Example to Understand

Suppose 10 users send requests.

Response times:

100 ms
120 ms
150 ms
200 ms
220 ms
250 ms
300 ms
350 ms
400 ms
5000 ms

Average:

= 709 ms

Looks okay, right?

But one request took 5000 ms (5 seconds).

This is why percentiles are used.

3. 90th Percentile (P90)

90% of requests finished within this time.
Example:
P90 = 400 ms
Meaning:
90% users got response ≤ 400 ms
10% users experienced slower responses
Real-life meaning:
This shows performance for most users.
4. 95th Percentile (P95)
Definition:
95% of requests finished within this time.
Example:
P95 = 700 ms
Meaning:
95% users experienced ≤ 700 ms
Only 5% were slower
This is one of the most used metrics in production systems.

Companies often define SLAs like:

95% of requests must complete under 2 seconds
5. 99th Percentile (P99)

Definition:

99% of requests finished within this time.

Example:

P99 = 3000 ms

Meaning:

99% users got response ≤ 3 sec

Only 1% users were slower

This helps detect extreme delays.

6. Visual Example

Imagine 100 requests sorted by response time.

Request 1   → 100 ms
Request 50  → 300 ms
Request 90  → 600 ms
Request 95  → 800 ms
Request 99  → 2500 ms
Request 100 → 6000 ms

Metrics become:

P90 = 600 ms
P95 = 800 ms
P99 = 2500 ms

Meaning:

90% users < 600 ms

95% users < 800 ms

99% users < 2500 ms

7. Why Average Is Not Reliable

Example:

Response Times
100 ms
200 ms
300 ms
400 ms
8000 ms

Average:

= 1800 ms

Looks slow.

But 80% users were actually fast.

Percentile shows the real picture.

