11. Golden Performance Rule

A good system should have:

Low latency
Low response time
High throughput
High concurrency handling


1. What is View Results in Table

View Results in Table displays each request result with important metrics like:

response time

status

latency

response code

thread name

Each row = one request execution.

You add it by:

Test Plan
  → Thread Group
      → HTTP Request
          → Listener
              → View Results in Table

Fields in View Results in Table

Typical columns look like this:

Sample #	Start Time	Thread Name	Label	Sample Time	Status	Bytes	Sent Bytes	Latency	Connect Time

Sample

Meaning:
Sequential number of request execution.

Example:

Sample #
1
2
3
4

Real-life meaning:

Helps identify which request occurred first.

Example:

Sample 25 failed

You can quickly locate it.

4. Start Time

Meaning:
Exact time when request started.

Example:

10:12:30.456

Real-life use:

Helps analyze when performance issues start.

Example:

Requests slow after 10:15

This may indicate server overload.

5. Thread Name

Meaning:
Shows which virtual user (thread) executed the request.

Example:

Thread Group 1-1
Thread Group 1-2
Thread Group 1-3

Interpretation:

Thread Group 1-5

means

User 5

Real-life meaning:

Helps identify which user simulation executed the request.

6. Label

Meaning:
Name of the request or sampler.

Example:

Label
Login API
Search API
Checkout API

Real-life meaning:

Identifies which API/page was executed.

7. Sample Time (ms)

Meaning:
Total response time for that request.

Formula:

Sample Time = request start → response fully received

Example:

Sample Time = 1500 ms

Meaning user waited 1.5 seconds.

Real-life meaning:

Shows actual user wait time.

8. Status

Shows whether request passed or failed.

Example:

Status
✔ success
✖ failure

Real-life meaning:

Failure could mean:

HTTP 500 error

timeout

assertion failure

connection issue

9. Bytes

Meaning:
Size of response received from server.

Example:

Bytes = 20480

Meaning:

20 KB response

Real-life meaning:

Large responses can slow performance.

Example:

product images

big JSON payloads

10. Sent Bytes

Meaning:
Size of request sent to server.

Example:

Sent Bytes = 350

Meaning request payload size.

Real-life meaning:

Large POST requests increase network load.

Example:

Uploading:

files

images

large JSON data

11. Latency

Meaning:
Time taken until first byte of response arrives.

Example:

Latency = 200 ms

Real-life meaning:

Shows network + server start delay.

If:

Latency high
Response time high

Then server processing might be slow.

12. Connect Time

Meaning:
Time taken to establish TCP connection with server.

Example:

Connect Time = 50 ms

Real-life meaning:

Includes:

DNS lookup

TCP handshake

SSL setup

If this is high → network issue.



What the Aggregate Graph Shows

The Aggregate Graph listener plots performance metrics calculated from all requests.

How to Add Aggregate Graph in JMeter

Steps:

Open Apache JMeter.

Right-click Thread Group.

Go to
Add → Listener → Aggregate Graph

Run your test.

The graph will automatically display results.

Example Scenario

Suppose you test a login API with 100 users.

After execution, the Aggregate Graph may show:

Label	Samples	Avg (ms)	90% Line	Error %	Throughput
Login API	100	320	450	0%	5/sec

Interpretation:

Average response = 320 ms

90% of requests completed under 450 ms

No failures

System handled 5 requests/sec

